er, Cumberland, England":"Muncaster, Cumberland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Pennington","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire and Cumbria):","habitational name from Pennington in Furness (Lancashire), which derives from Old English <i>pening</i> ‘penny’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, or from Pennington in Leigh (Lancashire), which probably derives from the Old English personal name <i>Pinna</i> + the Old English groupname suffix <i>-ingas</i> (genitive <i>-inga-</i>) + Old English <i>tūn</i>.","habitational name from Pennington (Hampshire), or from Penton Grafton or Penton Mewsey (both Hampshire); see   Penton  . All have the same etymology as Pennington in Furness; see 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Penington","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Pennington  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland.","History: Edward Penington, born in 1667 in Amersham, Buckinghamshire, England, was appointed surveyor-general of the province of PA in 1698 and accompanied William Penn to Philadelphia."]},{"name":"Penton","meanings":["English (mainly Hampshire):","habitational name from Penton Grafton or Penton Mewsey (both Hanmpshire), or from a shortened form of   Pennington   2. The placenames denoted a farm or estate for which a penny tax was payable (Old English <i>pening</i> ‘penny’ + <i>tūn</i>).","in north-west England, a shortened form of   Pennington   1, from either of the places called Pennington in Lancashire."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":20,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":45,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Pennington was born about 1270, in Pennington, Lancashire, England, his father, Sir Alan Pennington, was 38 and his mother, Lucretia de Radcliffe, was 47. He had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Alicia Molecastre. He died about 1323, in his hometown, at the age of 55."},"et":{"about 1270–about 1323":"